of
Nunnely
Wood;
divine
vignettes
of
mild
spring
or
mellow
autumn
moments,
when
she
had
sat
at
his
side
in
Hollow's
Copse,
listening
to
the
call
of
the
May
cuckoo,
or
sharing
the
September
treasure
of
nuts
and
ripe
blackberries
a
wild
dessert
which
it
was
her
morning's
pleasure
to
collect
in
a
little
basket,
and
cover
with
green
leaves
and
fresh
blossoms,
and
her
afternoon's
delight
to
administer
to
Moore,
berry
by
berry,
and
nut
by
nut,
like
a
bird
feeding
its
fledgling.
Robert's
features
and
form
were
with
her;
the
sound
of
his
voice
was
quite
distinct
in
